05866nam a22006015i 9780804765916DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221997cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047659167 a10.1515/97808047659162doi  a(DE-B1597)581718  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0042902bisacsh00aWriting Women in Late Imperial China /ced. by Ellen Widmer, Kang-i Sun Chang. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (560 p.) :b38 illus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Writing the Courtesan -- t1 Ambiguous Images of Courtesan Culture in Late Imperial China -- t2 The Late Ming Courtesan: Invention of a Cultural Ideal -- t3 The Written Word and the Bound Foot: A History of the Courtesan's Aura -- t4 Desire and Writing in the Late Ming Play Parrot Island -- t5 Women in Feng Menglong's Mountain Songs -- tPart II: Norms and Selves -- t6 Ming and Qing Anthologies of Women's Poetry and Their Selection Strategies -- t7 Changing the Subject: Gender and Self-inscription in Authors' Prefaces and "Shi" Poetry -- tPart III: Poems in Context -- t8 Writing Her Way Out of Trouble: Li Yuying in History and Fiction -- t9 Embodying the Disembodied: Representations of Ghosts and the Feminine -- t10 De/Constructing a Feminine Ideal in the Eighteenth Century: Random Records of West-Green and the Story of Shuangqing -- tPart IV: "Hong lou meng" -- t11 Women's Writing Before and Within the Hong lou meng -- t12 Beyond Stereotypes: The Twelve Beauties in Qing Court Art and the Dream of the Red Chamber -- t13 Ming Loyalism and the Woman's Voice in Fiction After Hong lou meng -- tPostface: Chinese Women in a Comparative Perspective: A Response -- tReference Matter -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tCharacter List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUntil recently only a handful of women writers were thought to have existed in traditional China, but new scholarship has called attention to several hundred whose works have survived. Coming from the fields of literature, history, art history, and comparative literature, the fourteen contributors to this volume apply a range of methodologies to this new material and to other sources concerning women writers in China from 1600 to 1900. An opening section on courtesans details the lives of individual women and their male admirers—contemporary and subsequent—who imposed an array of meaning on the category of woman writer. The works treated in this section are mainly poetry, although drama also enters in. The second section focuses on the writings of gentrywomen who, confined to the inner quarters of their residences, turned out a body of poetry impressive both for its volume and for the number of authors involved. The third section takes up the issue of contextualization: how male writers situated women's poetry in their essays, stories, and travelogues. The fourth section pursues the same issue, but with reference to China's greatest work of fiction, Dream of the Red Chamber, first published in 1792, most of whose leading characters are talented gentrywomen. The volume concludes with a chapter by a specialist in comparative literature, who relates the concerns of the other chapters to literary and feminist studies outside the China field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlitz, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Kang-i Sun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular